  <mainDescription>Requirements initially are high level, but progressively become more detailed as more is known and understood. They need to
        be written in such a way that they are unambiguous (i.e. measurable and testable), traceable and complete. They must be
        accepted/approved by the stakeholder(s).&lt;br style=&quot;font-family: Candara;&quot; />
         &lt;br style=&quot;font-family: Candara;&quot; />
         The format of a requirements document ranges from a simple listing of all the requirements categorized and prioritized, to
        a more detailed one with descriptions and attachments.&lt;br style=&quot;font-family: Candara;&quot; />
         &lt;br style=&quot;font-family: Candara;&quot; />
         Requirements documentation include, but are not limited to:&lt;br style=&quot;font-family: Candara;&quot; />
         &lt;br style=&quot;font-family: Candara;&quot; />
         
        &lt;ul>
            &lt;li>
                Business requirements such as business and project objectives for tracebility, business rules and guiding
                principles of the organization.
            &lt;/li>
            &lt;li>
                Stakeholder requirements including impacts to other departments or organizations
            &lt;/li>
            &lt;li>
                Solution requirements including functional and non-functional, technology, compliance, support and training,
                quality and reporting requirements
            &lt;/li>
            &lt;li>
                Project requirements including service, performance, safety and compiance level of service along with project
                acceptance criteria
            &lt;/li>
            &lt;li>
                Requirements assumptions, dependencies and constraints
            &lt;/li>
        &lt;/ul></mainDescription>
  <impactOfNotHaving>If there are no requirements, there can be no project. These are the heart of any project.&lt;br /></impactOfNotHaving>
  <reasonsForNotNeeding>Written requirements may not be necessary if the project requirements are obvious to all stakeholders.&lt;br /></reasonsForNotNeeding>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription>
